We will calculate the following ratios using the "End_amount" values in the provided balance sheet and cash flow statement as of 2024‐01‐29.

Step 1. Current Ratio

• Current Ratio = (Total Current Assets) / (Total Current Liabilities)

From the balance sheet:
 Total Current Assets = 10,333,889.03  
 Total Current Liabilities = 1,124,588.25

Calculation:
 Current Ratio = 10,333,889.03 / 1,124,588.25 ≈ 9.19

Step 2. Quick Ratio

• Quick Ratio = (Current Assets – Inventory) / (Current Liabilities)

Subtract Inventory from Total Current Assets:
 Inventory = 975,000.00  
 Quick Assets = 10,333,889.03 – 975,000.00 = 9,358,889.03

Then,
 Quick Ratio = 9,358,889.03 / 1,124,588.25 ≈ 8.32

Step 3. Debt to Asset Ratio

• Debt to Asset Ratio = (Total Liabilities) / (Total Assets)

In this balance sheet, Total Liabilities (only current liabilities) = 1,124,588.25 and
 Total Assets = 15,288,131.32

Thus,
 Debt to Asset Ratio = 1,124,588.25 / 15,288,131.32 ≈ 0.07

Step 4. Debt to Equity Ratio

• Debt to Equity Ratio = (Total Liabilities) / (Total Owner’s Equity)

From the balance sheet:
 Total Owner’s Equity = 14,163,543.07

Then,
 Debt to Equity Ratio = 1,124,588.25 / 14,163,543.07 ≈ 0.08

Step 5. Cash Flow to Debt Ratio

• Cash Flow to Debt Ratio = (Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities) / (Total Liabilities)

From the cash flow statement:
 Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities = 215,423.24  
 Total Liabilities = 1,124,588.25

Thus,
 Cash Flow to Debt Ratio = 215,423.24 / 1,124,588.25 ≈ 0.19

The final answer in the required json format is:

{
  "solution": {
    "Current Ratio": "9.19",
    "Quick Ratio": "8.32",
    "Debt to Asset Ratio": "0.07",
    "Debt to Equity Ratio": "0.08",
    "Cash Flow to Debt Ratio": "0.19"
  }
}
